.SS 2. The Courtroom Dynamic
You probably know this critical fact about your performance review:
\f[B]You are not in the room.\f[R]
.PP
Your evaluation is not a standardized test where you fill in the bubbles
and a machine grades you.
It is a \f[B]litigation\f[R].
It is a trial by jury, held in absentia.
.PP
Once you understand that the Calibration Meeting is a courtroom, the
roles become clear.
.SS The Defendant: You
You are on trial.
Your compensation, your title, and your future leverage are on the
docket.
But because you are not allowed in the room, you cannot speak for
yourself.
.SS The Defense Attorney: Your Manager
This is the most important reframe in your career.
Your manager is not your \(lqboss\(rq during calibration; they are your
court\-appointed counsel.
.PP
Most engineers treat 1:1s as \(lqstatus updates\(rq or
\(lqconfessionals.\(rq This is a strategic error.
A 1:1 is \f[B]legal discovery\f[R].
.PP
If you walk into a 1:1 and say, \(lqI\(cqm struggling with this API,\(rq
you are handing your attorney bad facts.
.PP
If you walk in and say, \(lqI just shipped X, which solved Y for Team
Z,\(rq you are handing them \f[B]Exhibits A, B, and C\f[R].
.PP
Your attorney (Manager) is likely tired, overworked, and managing 6
other cases.
If you do not hand them the prepared brief\(emthe status\-weighted
stories\(emthey will not have the energy to invent a defense for you.
They will plea bargain you down to \(lqMeets Expectations\(rq to save
their political capital for a client who gave them better evidence.
.SS The Prosecution / Jury: Your Manager\(cqs Peers
Here is where the \(lqTeam Player\(rq myth dies.
.PP
The other managers in the room are not your friends.
They are your Manager\(cqs Peers (S_i nodes in the Cylinder).
.PP
They are acting as both \f[B]Jury\f[R] and \f[B]Prosecution\f[R].
.PP
Why prosecution?
Because the budget is finite.
The \(lqExceeds Expectations\(rq rating is a scarce resource (often
capped at 10\-20% of the pool).
.PP
For Manager A to get a promotion for \f[I]their\f[R] star engineer, they
effectively need to argue that \f[I]you\f[R] do not deserve one.
It is a zero\-sum game of horse\-trading.
.SS The Judge: The Skip\-Level (Director/VP)
The Judge sits at the head of the table.
They often don\(cqt know your name, or if they do, they know it as a
variable in a spreadsheet.
.PP
They care about three things:
.IP "1." 3
