.SH Tactics I: Karma\-Driven Development (KDD)
In software engineering, the most disciplined teams practice
\f[B]Test\-Driven Development (TDD)\f[R].
The rule is simple: \f[B]Red, Green, Refactor.\f[R]
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]Red:\f[R] Write a test that fails (because the feature doesn\(cqt
exist yet).
.IP "2." 3
\f[B]Green:\f[R] Write just enough code to make the test pass.
.IP "3." 3
\f[B]Refactor:\f[R] Clean up the code.
.PP
Despite this, most \f[I]careers\f[R] run on \f[B]Waterfall\f[R].
You do months of work, ship it, and then hope that the calibration court
validates your work.
This is madness.
You are building features without a spec.
.PP
To fix this, adopt \f[B]Karma\-Driven Development (KDD)\f[R].
In this framework, you never write a line of code until you have written
the performance review bullet point that rewards it.
.IP
