.SS Phase 1: Echolocation (Witness Selection & The IKEA Hook)
Before you can write a test, you need requirements.
.PP
Right now, your mental backlog is likely full of \(lqTechnical Debt\(rq
and \(lqCool Ideas.\(rq You cannot sort this list by \f[B]Technical
Merit\f[R] (Private Ledger).
You must sort it by \f[B]Market Demand\f[R] (Firm Ledger).
.PP
Scan your local area of the corporate social network, including (but not
limited to) your Calibration Cylinder .
Find a high\-status Witness (S_i) who needs a problem solved.
But do not just ask them what to do.
.PP
If you ask \f[I]\(lqWhat should I work on?\(rq\f[R], you are an
execution\-bot.
You are a commodity.
Instead, you goal is to trigger the \f[B]IKEA Effect\f[R].
.RS
.PP
\f[B]The IKEA Effect:\f[R] A cognitive bias in which consumers place a
disproportionately high value on products they partially created.
.RE
.PP
You want your Witness to feel like they had a hand in steering your
project.
If they design the box, they will love the box.
To do this, you must use \f[B]Political Echolocation\f[R]\(empinging the
network with a calibrated question to see what signal returns.
