.SH Tactics II: Manufacturing Evidence (The Brief)
In the previous chapter, you learned Karma Driven Development (KDD), a
strategy for choosing Status\-Weighted Stories \f[I]first\f[R] and
working backwards to make them true.
Now it\(cqs time to learn how to optimize that evidence for your manager
to bring to calibration court.
.PP
Your manager is tired.
They have six other cases to litigate.
They do not remember that cool bug fix you did in March.
.PP
In the lead up to your performance review, if you ask your manager to
\(lqlook at my commits,\(rq you are asking your lawyer to investigate
the crime scene ten minutes before the trial starts.
You will lose.
.PP
Your job is to hand them a fully formed \f[B]Legal Brief\f[R].
This is a document that requires zero cognitive load to copy\-paste into
the HR portal.
.PP
But how do you write a brief that survives the adversarial environment
of the Calibration Cylinder?
For that you have to understand the psychology of the jury.
.SS 1. Feeding the Numerophiles
Your evaluators (Directors, VPs, Senior Peers) are human beings, but
they are a specific type.
They are \f[B]Numerophiles\f[R].
.PP
They are impressed by quantification.
In the absence of trust, they use numbers as a proxy for truth.
A paragraph of prose feels like an \(lqopinion.\(rq A scatter plot feels
like \(lqscience.\(rq
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Bad:\f[R] \(lqI significantly improved the performance of the login
page.\(rq (Hearsay).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Good:\f[R] \(lqReduced P99 login latency by \f[B]230ms
(\-14%)\f[R], reclaiming \f[B]45 engineering\-hours\f[R] per month in
wait time.\(rq (Fact).
.PP
It does not matter that the \(lq45 hours\(rq is a napkin\-math estimate.
It is a \f[B]Number\f[R].
It has significant digits.
It triggers the \(lqTruth\(rq receptor in the evaluator\(cqs brain.
Defensible estimates are in bounds.
.SS 2. Moral Targeting (Know Your Judge)
Before you pick your number, you must pick your narrative.
This goes back to \f[B]CVE\-DEW\-03 (The Motivation Mismatch)\f[R].
You must frame your achievement in a way that strokes the specific
\f[I]motivations\f[R] of your evaluators.
.PP
Different tribes worship different gods:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]The Sales/Exec Tribe:\f[R] Worships \f[B]Authority\f[R] and
\f[B]Revenue\f[R].
They care about speed, dollars, and \(lqwinning.\(rq
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]The Old Guard/Sysadmin Tribe:\f[R] Worships \f[B]Sanctity\f[R] and
\f[B]Order\f[R].
They care about stability, uptime, and \(lqdoing it the right way.\(rq
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]The Modern SV/HR Tribe:\f[R] Worships \f[B]Care/Harm\f[R] and
\f[B]Fairness\f[R].
They care about \(lqUser Delight,\(rq \(lqInclusivity,\(rq and
\(lqDemocratizing Access.\(rq
.PP
You must estimate the moral composition of your org in general and the
Calibration Court in particular, then tailor your evidence accordingly.
